The Kenya National Union of Teachers has suspended the September 1 strike pending a meeting with the Teachers Service Commission. Speaking to the Star yesterday, Knut secretary general Wilson Sossion said the industrial action has been put on hold to give room for negotiations.“We hope to find a solution to avoid disruption of teaching and learning in third term,” Sossion said. The policies the teachers’ union opposes included delocalisation, promotion of teachers with higher qualifications and performance appraisal. Click here for the latest political news